    "what_description": "Thymus vulgaris is a perennial herbaceous plant belonging to the family Lamiaceae, commonly known as the mint or deadnettle family. It has a woody base and branches that are 20-30 cm long, with linear or lanceolate leaves that are 6-10 mm long, grayish-green in color, and have a crenate margin. The leaves are oppositely arranged on the stem, and the plant produces small, tubular, pinkish or purplish flowers in axillary whorls, which are 6-8 mm long and contain 4 lobes. The flowers are arranged in a corymb, and the calyx is 5-6 mm long, with 5 triangular lobes. The plant has a fibrous root system and is native to the Mediterranean region, but it is now cultivated worldwide for its leaves and essential oil.",
