    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Thymus vulgaris are thymol, carvacrol, linalool, p-cymene, and borneol. Thymol is a potent antimicrobial agent with a broad spectrum of activity, effective against bacteria, viruses, and fungi, inhibiting the growth of pathogens through disruption of cell membranes and interference with DNA replication. Carvacrol is a natural antioxidant and anti-inflammatory compound, exhibiting cytotoxic activity against cancer cells and modulating the immune system to enhance its response to infection. Linalool has been shown to possess antiseptic and anti-inflammatory properties, while also exhibiting anxiolytic and sedative effects, contributing to its calming and relaxing properties. P-cymene and borneol, which are also present in Thymus vulgaris, contribute to its antioxidant and anti-inflammatory activities, with p-cymene exhibiting antimicrobial properties and borneol possessing anti-inflammatory and antiseptic effects.",
