    "preparations_description": "The main herbal preparations of Thymus vulgaris are made to utilize its carvacrol and thymol content, which exhibit antimicrobial, antifungal, and anti-inflammatory properties. Thyme tea, a liquid extract made by steeping the leaves in hot water, is used to treat respiratory issues like coughs and bronchitis due to its expectorant properties. Thyme tincture, a concentrated liquid extract, is often used to treat digestive issues, such as bloating and indigestion, due to its carminative and anti-inflammatory effects. Thyme oil, a highly concentrated essential oil, is used topically to treat skin issues like acne, wounds, and fungal infections due to its antimicrobial properties, while also being used in aromatherapy for its calming effects. Thyme infusion, a liquid extract made by steeping the leaves in cold water, is similar to thyme tea but has a milder flavor and is often used to make thyme salve, a topical preparation made with beeswax and oil that is used to treat skin issues like eczema and dermatitis.",
